Size. Known adult size about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F60FFF7FE07FAA0FDFDFAA1" box="[486,541,1318,1344]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" unit="cm" value="6.0">6 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F60FFF4FF26FACCFB8BFEFF" lastPageId="86" lastPageNumber="87" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F60FFF7FF26FACCFBABFA15" blockId="85.[151,1437,1318,2028]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
Morphology. D V–VI + I,10–12; A I,10; P 17–20. Body relatively short, laterally compressed. Head moderately long, with a steep snout profile. Anterior nostril tubular, with no dermal process from its rim. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin with more or less rounded margin. The uppermost pectoral-fin rays are within the membrane with no free rays (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F60FFF7FC3CFA30FB8AFA31" author="Miller, P. J." box="[989,1130,1462,1488]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="831 - 855" refId="ref61142" refString="Miller, P. J. (1969) Systematics and biology of the leopard-spotted goby, Gobius ephippiatus [Teleostei: Gobiidae], with description of a new genus and notes on the identity of G. macrolepis Kolombatovic. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 49 (4), 831 - 855. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 002531540003798 X" type="journal article" year="1969">Miller 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F60FFF7FB96FA30FA70FA31" author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[1143,1424,1462,1488]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="149 - 162" refId="ref50280" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Kovacic, M. (1997) A northern Adriatic population of Thorogobius macrolepis (Gobiidae). Cybium, 21 (2), 149 - 162. https: // doi. org / 10.19233 / ASHN. 2016.18" type="journal article" year="1997">Ahnelt &amp; Kovačić 1997</bibRefCitation>
). Scales present on body, usually poorly visible on photographs. Predorsal area naked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F60FFF7FF26FA78FDA6F8D9" blockId="85.[151,1437,1318,2028]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
Live coloration. Ground coloration white to light gray with a light blue sheen on the back and pearly white markings ventrally. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F60FFF7FE61F9A7FC89F9DD" bold="true" box="[384,873,1569,1596]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Orange to yellow-orange spots on body</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F60FFF7FC9CF9A4FC26F9DC" box="[893,966,1570,1597]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1757,1781]" captionTargetBox="[150,1435,873,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-39@15.[150,1435,873,1733]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Thorogobius macrolepis. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601581" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601581/files/figure.png" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F60FFF7FC01F9A7FAF7F981" bold="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Five brick red to orange midlateral blotches, 2 to 3 times longer than deeper, each blotch sometimes appearing as 2 contiguous spots.</emphasis>
Interspaces between blotches often pearly white. Many short line segments, horizontal or oblique, each of 3-5 light orange dots, above the lateral midline. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F60FFF7FE19F908FCEBF92D" bold="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Head and predorsal area covered with many orange spots larger than the dots of the back but smaller than the midlateral blotches.</emphasis>
No V-shaped mark on snout (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F60FFF7FBBCF934FB42F92C" box="[1117,1186,1714,1741]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1757,1781]" captionTargetBox="[150,1435,873,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-39@15.[150,1435,873,1733]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 6. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Thorogobius macrolepis. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601581" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601581/files/figure.png" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). One orange, oblique preorbital bar extending onto the upper lip; otherwise the lips are white. Dorsal fins blue-gray with three orange transverse bands and a broader whitish to 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F60FFF7FD98F97FFC4DF8F5" bold="true" box="[633,941,1785,1812]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">light blue marginal band.</emphasis>
Caudal fin also blue gray with 3-4 sinuous orange bars (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F60FFF7FEC6F898FDDAF8D9" author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[295,570,1822,1848]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="149 - 162" refId="ref50280" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Kovacic, M. (1997) A northern Adriatic population of Thorogobius macrolepis (Gobiidae). Cybium, 21 (2), 149 - 162. https: // doi. org / 10.19233 / ASHN. 2016.18" type="journal article" year="1997">Ahnelt &amp; Kovačić 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F60FFF7FF26F8C4FC43F8BD" blockId="85.[151,1437,1318,2028]" box="[199,931,1858,1884]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F60FFF7FE9EF8C4FD96F8BD" authorityName="Kovacic &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2000" box="[383,630,1858,1884]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kolombatovici">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F60FFF7FE9EF8C4FD96F8BD" box="[383,630,1858,1884]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Gobius kolombatovici</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F60FFF7FD65F8C4FC7CF8BD" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Lowe" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[644,924,1858,1884]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Thorogobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ephippiatus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F60FFF7FD65F8C4FC7CF8BD" box="[644,924,1858,1884]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Thorogobius ephippiatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F60FFF7FF26F8E0FAA6F845" blockId="85.[151,1437,1318,2028]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
Habitat. Infralittoral and circalittoral species, known from 
<quantity id="2E379B383F60FFF7FC84F8E0FC5CF861" box="[869,956,1894,1920]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" unit="m" value="33.0" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="6.0">6–60 m</quantity>
depth, on detritic coarse sand and gravel, close to rocky shelters, typically at the foot of rocky walls (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F60FFF7FCCEF80CFBB4F845" author="Glavicic, I. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[815,1108,1930,1956]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="43 - 47" refId="ref55156" refString="Glavicic, I. &amp; Kovacic, M. (2016) A quantitative sampling method for assessment of deep cryptobenthic ichthyofauna using trimix diving. Acta Ichthyologica et Piscatoria, 46 (1), 43 - 47. https: // doi. org / 10.3750 / AIP 2016.46.1.06" type="journal article" year="2016">Glavičić &amp; Kovačić 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
